  variant="plain"
&gt;</span></div>

<p><span class="winner-tag green">Winner: semver/goose</span></p>
</div>
</details>

<!-- 6.9 Icon component -->
<details id="detail-icon">
<summary>🔷 Icon Component Usage in ResponseToolModal</summary>
<div class="details-content">
<h4>What changed in PF6</h4>
<p>The <code>Icon</code> component still exists in PF6 but its usage pattern has shifted. In the goose branch, the <code>Icon</code> wrapper was removed in favor of rendering icons directly. This is a stylistic simplification that aligns with PF6's preference for using icons without unnecessary wrapper components.</p>

<h4>Before (main) — <code>ResponseToolModal.tsx</code></h4>
<div class="code-block"><span class="code-del">import { ..., Icon, ... } from '@patternfly/react-core';
...
&lt;Icon isInline status={isDenied ? undefined : status === 'error' ? 'danger' : 'info'}&gt;
  {isDenied ? (
    &lt;BanIcon color="var(--pf-t--global--icon--color--subtle)" /&gt;
  ) : (
    &lt;InfoCircleIcon /&gt;
  )}
&lt;/Icon&gt;</span></div>

<h4>After (semver/goose)</h4>
<div class="code-block"><span class="code-add">{isDenied ? (
  &lt;BanIcon color="var(--pf-t--global--icon--color--subtle)" /&gt;
) : (
  &lt;InfoCircleIcon /&gt;
)}</span></div>

<p><strong>Note:</strong> This change removes the <code>status</code> prop-based coloring from <code>Icon</code>, which would have applied status colors (info blue / danger red) to the icon. The modal title already provides context through text ("Tool call rejected" vs "Tool output"), so the impact is minor and visual only. This is a slight functional regression but in a non-critical area.</p>

<p><span class="winner-tag green">Winner: semver/goose</span> (with minor caveat about status coloring loss)</p>
</div>
</details>

<!-- 6.10 Chatbot ts-expect-error -->
<details id="detail-chatbot">
<summary>💬 Chatbot @ts-expect-error Cleanup</summary>
<div class="details-content">
<h4>Background</h4>
<p>The main branch has 12 <code>@ts-expect-error: TS2786</code> suppressions in <code>GeneralPage.tsx</code> (11) and <code>Prompt.tsx</code> (1). These suppress TypeScript errors caused by <code>@patternfly/chatbot</code> components being typed for React 18 while the project uses React 17 types.</p>

<h4>Root cause</h4>
<p>TS2786 occurs when a component's JSX type is incompatible with the JSX factory. React 17's <code>@types/react</code> uses a different JSX element type than React 18, causing chatbot components to fail type-checking.</p>

<h4>semver/goose fix</h4>
<p>By upgrading to <code>@types/react@18</code>, the chatbot components' types are now compatible. All 12 <code>@ts-expect-error</code> suppressions were removed cleanly.</p>

<h4>Evidence</h4>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>File</th><th>main</th><th>pf-codemods</th><th>semver/goose</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>GeneralPage.tsx</td><td style="color:var(--red)">11 suppressions</td><td style="color:var(--red)">11 suppressions</td><td style="color:var(--green)">0 suppressions</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Prompt.tsx</td><td style="color:var(--red)">1 suppression</td><td style="color:var(--red)">1 suppression</td><td style="color:var(--green)">0 suppressions</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p><span class="winner-tag green">Winner: semver/goose</span></p>
</div>
</details>

<!-- 6.11 Trans component -->
<details id="detail-trans">
<summary>🌐 Trans Component i18n Fix</summary>
<div class="details-content">
<h4>What changed</h4>
<p>In <code>ResponseToolModal.tsx</code>, the <code>&lt;Trans&gt;</code> component usage was updated from embedded interpolation <code>{{ name }}</code> to explicit <code>values</code> prop with <code>{'{{name}}'}</code> string template markers.</p>

<h4>Before (main)</h4>
<div class="code-block"><span class="code-del">&lt;Trans&gt;
  The tool &lt;span className="ols-plugin__code-inline"&gt;{{ name }}&lt;/span&gt; was requested
  with arguments &lt;span className="ols-plugin__code-inline"&gt;{{ argsFormatted }}&lt;/span&gt;
  but was rejected.
&lt;/Trans&gt;</span></div>

<h4>After (semver/goose)</h4>
<div class="code-block"><span class="code-add">&lt;Trans values={{ name, argsFormatted }}&gt;
  The tool &lt;span className="ols-plugin__code-inline"&gt;{'{{name}}'}&lt;/span&gt; was requested
  with arguments &lt;span className="ols-plugin__code-inline"&gt;{'{{argsFormatted}}'}&lt;/span&gt;
  but was rejected.
&lt;/Trans&gt;</span></div>

<h4>Analysis</h4>
<p>This change is related to the React 18 upgrade. The old pattern of using <code>{{ name }}</code> directly as JSX children inside <code>&lt;Trans&gt;</code> relied on implicit object spreading behavior that's stricter in React 18's type system. The new pattern explicitly passes values via the <code>values</code> prop, which is the officially recommended react-i18next approach. This is a correctness improvement.</p>

<p><span class="winner-tag green">Winner: semver/goose</span></p>
</div>
</details>

<!-- 6.12 ImmutableMap -->
<details id="detail-immutable">
<summary>📊 ImmutableMap .toArray() Fix</summary>
<div class="details-content">
<h4>What changed</h4>
<p>In <code>OlsToolUIs.tsx</code>, <code>.valueSeq()</code> was followed by <code>.toArray()</code> to convert the Immutable.js sequence to a plain array.</p>

<h4>Before (main)</h4>
<div class="code-block"><span class="code-del">.map(({ tool, toolUIComponent }, toolID) =&gt; (
  &lt;OlsToolUI key={...} tool={tool} toolUIComponent={toolUIComponent} /&gt;
))
.valueSeq()}</span></div>

<h4>After (semver/goose)</h4>
<div class="code-block"><span class="code-add">.map(({ tool, toolUIComponent }, toolID) =&gt; (
  &lt;OlsToolUI key={...} tool={tool} toolUIComponent={toolUIComponent} /&gt;
))
.valueSeq()
.toArray()}</span></div>

<h4>Analysis</h4>
<p>React 18 is stricter about the types of children it accepts. Immutable.js's <code>Seq</code> type is not a valid React child array in React 18 types. Adding <code>.toArray()</code> converts it to a plain <code>Array</code>, which React accepts. This is a necessary fix for the React 18 upgrade.</p>

<p><span class="winner-tag green">Winner: semver/goose</span></p>
</div>
</details>

<!-- 6.13 Webpack -->
<details id="detail-webpack">
<summary>⚙️ Webpack Configuration</summary>
<div class="details-content">
<h4>What changed</h4>
<p>In <code>webpack.config.ts</code>, the goose branch added <code>validateSharedModules: false</code> to <code>ConsoleRemotePlugin()</code>.</p>

<h4>Before (main)</h4>
<div class="code-block"><span class="code-del">new ConsoleRemotePlugin(),</span></div>

<h4>After (semver/goose)</h4>
<div class="code-block"><span class="code-add">new ConsoleRemotePlugin({ validateSharedModules: false }),</span></div>

<h4>Analysis</h4>
<p>This disables shared module validation in the OpenShift Console plugin webpack plugin. This is likely needed because the React 18 upgrade changes the shared module versions (React, ReactDOM) and the Console's built-in validation may flag the version mismatch since the Console itself may still expect React 17. This is a pragmatic workaround for the version gap.</p>

<p><span class="winner-tag green">Winner: semver/goose</span> (necessary for the React 18 upgrade)</p>
</div>
</details>

<!-- 6.14 Scope Discipline -->
<details id="detail-scope">
<summary>🎯 Scope Discipline</summary>
<div class="details-content">
<h4>pf-codemods-053126-0158</h4>
<p>This branch has <strong>perfect scope discipline</strong> in the trivial sense: it changed nothing. The single file changed (<code>.cache_1l6xbui</code>) is a codemod cache artifact that should not have been committed. This is not scope discipline — it is absence of work.</p>

<h4>semver/goose/053126-0138</h4>
<p>Every change in this branch is directly attributable to the PatternFly migration:</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Change</th><th>Migration justification</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>React 17→18</td><td>Required by @patternfly/chatbot 6.x peer dependency</td></tr>
    <tr><td>react-redux 7→9</td><td>react-redux 7.x doesn't support React 18</td></tr>
    <tr><td>@types/react 17→18</td><td>Required for React 18</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Remove react overrides</td><td>No longer needed with React 18</td></tr>
    <tr><td>CSS pf-v5 → pf-t tokens</td><td>Official PF6 token migration</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ModalBody wrappers</td><td>PF6 composable Modal pattern</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Label icon prop</td><td>PF6 Label API</td></tr>
    <tr><td>MenuToggle icon prop</td><td>PF6 MenuToggle API</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Dropdown onSelect typing</td><td>PF6 Dropdown API</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ClipboardCopyButton textId</td><td>PF6 deprecated prop removal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Icon wrapper removal</td><td>PF6 simplification</td></tr>
    <tr><td>@ts-expect-error removal</td><td>React 18 types fix chatbot compatibility</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Trans values prop</td><td>React 18 type strictness</td></tr>
    <tr><td>.toArray() on ImmutableMap</td><td>React 18 children type strictness</td></tr>
    <tr><td>webpack validateSharedModules</td><td>React 18 shared module compatibility</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ScrollBehavior type annotation</td><td>React 18 type strictness</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>No unrelated refactors, feature additions, or architectural changes were found.</strong> The only arguable item is the Icon component removal, which could be considered a minor simplification rather than a strict requirement. The Trans component change and .toArray() change are necessary consequences of the React 18 upgrade.</p>

<p><span class="winner-tag green">Winner: semver/goose</span> — excellent scope discipline with all changes traceable to the migration.</p>
</div>
</details>

